cs.CG, cs.DS, cs.DM, cs.CC, cs.SI. 

The paper deals with algorithms for computing optimal rotations of necklaces, which involves geometric and combinatorial aspects, suggesting that it could belong to cs.CG (Computational Geometry) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). The use of convolution algorithms also suggests that it could belong to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity). Finally, the mention of the sorting X + Y problem and its connection to the convolutions suggests that it could belong to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
